    <text type="letter">  
        <body>
            <pb xml:id="leaf001r" facs="loc_jm.00202.jpg" type="recto"/>
            <opener>
                <dateline>
                    <name type="place" rend="left">Williamsburgh,</name>
                    <date when="1852-03-31">March 31.</date>
                    <name type="place">145 Grand St.<ptr target="loc.03673_n2"/></name>
                </dateline>
                <salute>Mr. Whitman,</salute>
                <salute>Dr Sir,&#8212;</salute>
            </opener>
            <p>Mr. Twombly<ptr target="loc.003673_n1"/> and myself are about to commence the
                publication of a new weekly journal; devoted to the interests of Brooklyn, (for
                which we have received much encouragement,) and think we could give you a good
                position upon it. Our printing office will be here, but we wish a publication office
                near the City Hall, and an editor who will take charge of it. I wish you would call
                on us, at 145 Grand St., as soon as you can if you desire to have a connection with
                us.</p>
            <closer>
                <salute rend="right">Respectfully Yours</salute>
                <signed rend="right">Aaron Smith</signed>
            </closer>
            <pb xml:id="leaf001v" facs="loc_jm.00203.jpg" type="verso"/>
            <pb xml:id="leaf002r" facs="loc_jm.00204.jpg" type="recto"/>
            <note type="editorial" resp="#unk" place="left">from Aaron Smith of Williamsburgh about
                new paper</note>
        </body>
